They play a crucial role in controlling the phy- siological function of the genome and in DNA processes of replication, transcription recombination repair and chromosome decondensation [3,4]. Hence these enzymes serve as attractive targets for designing new antibacterial drugs. Topoisomerase inhibitors act as an obstacle to the ligation step in the microbial (gram positive and gram negative) cell cycle, generating single and double stranded breaks that damage the integrity of the genome leading to apoptosis (cell death) in the pro- liferating cell [5]. DNA gyrase is a type IIA topoisomerase belonging to gyrase, heat-shock protein 90 (Hsp 90) histidine kinase MutL (GHKL), protein kinases and the DNA mismatch repair protein MutL (Mismatch from replication recognized by mutL)) family of enzymes. DNA gyrase is classiﬁed as topoisomerase II, an ATP-dependent enzyme that is vital in the transcription, re- plication of DNA and chromosome segregation processes. It plays a crucial role in all bacteria except higher eukaryotes and this makes it a desirable and viable therapeutic target for development of new antibacterial agents. Fluoroquinolones are commonly used eﬀective antibacterial agents that target DNA gyrase, however the spectrum of side-eﬀects and emerging bacterial resistance with no new drugs in the antibacterial pipeline has fuelled intensive research in this area. New chemical entities with varied scaﬀolds possessing DNA gyrase in- hibiting properties have been determined by screening chemical libraries that could serve as good leads for antibacterial drug development. A wide range of natural products and protein-based compounds have been identiﬁed and studied as DNA gyrase inhibitors and this adds a huge amount of structural diversity that can be exploited and harnessed in the discovery of new antibacterial agents. The development of new chemical com- pounds with DNA gyrase inhibitory activity (from natural sources, random screens or rational design) will further validate/corroborate the potential of this enzyme as a useful target. This review presents an overview of the DNA gyrase inhibitors obtained from natural and synthetic sources, their syntheses schemes and spectrum of biological activity of a variety of scaﬀolds and their analogues. The authors hope to provide focused direction for development of new chemical entities, synthetic routes for analogue synthesis, structure activity relationships and biological activity. The most potent ones can be used as templates to design novel compounds targeting DNA gyrase and are eﬀective against resistant bacterial strains and bioﬁlms. It is one of the most investigated and validated targets for the development of new antibacterial agents. Its absence in the mammalian organism and its crucial role in the bacterial DNA replication cycle makes this enzyme a suitable target for the development of antibacterial drugs with selective toxicity. It comprises of two subunits-gyrase A and gyrase B that together form the catalytically active heterotetrameric enzyme (i.e. A2B2). The role of the A subunit is breakage and reunion of the double DNA strand, while the B subunit (DNA gyrase B) possesses the ATPase activity, providing a suﬃcient amount of energy for the DNA supercoiling [6–9]. DNA gyrase being a highly appealing drug target, a large number of inhibitors have been synthesized and characterized with quinolones and aminocoumarins being the most widely studied compounds [10].

Currently, the 6-ﬂuoroquinolones class of compounds are the only DNA gyrase inhibitors used in clinical practice. The quinolones create re- striction in the process of rejoining double-strand breaks in DNA while aminocoumarins and cyclothialidines (cyclic peptides) block the AT- Pase activity of DNA gyrase [11,12]. In addition to the above com- pounds, two proteinaceous poisons, microcin B17 and CcdB block Es- cherichia coli gyrase in a manner similar to that of quinolones. Most of these inhibitors fall into two groups based on their site of action and mechanism of inhibition: inhibitors such as ﬂuoroquinolones, CcdB and microcin B17 aﬀect the cleavage–religation step, while coumarins and cyclothialidines prevent ATP hydrolysis [13]. Despite the potency of existing drugs, several bacterial strains resistant to the current ther- apeutic regimen have emerged. This review aims to classify DNA gyrase inhibitors based on their source into drugs obtained from natural re- sources and drugs of synthetic origin. DNA gyrase is a validated target for the development of antimicrobial drugs hence synthesis of novel gyrase inhibitors is a highly active research area. This review also summarizes the current strategies utilized for discovery and synthesis of new chemical scaﬀolds as potential DNA gyrase inhibitors. 2. Classiﬁcation and functions of topoisomerases

Topoisomerases play an essential role in all organisms since they control and maintain the topological state of the DNA in the cell [14]. DNA cleavage in all topoisomerases enzyme is followed by the emer- gence of a transient phosphodiester bond between tyrosine residues in the protein. Role of DNA gyrase in DNA synthesis DNA gyrase is A2B2 heterotetrameric enzyme, comprising of two subunits of GyrA and GyrB each. Subunit A is composed of two do- mains. DNA gyrase inhibitors from natural origin The earliest of drugs have been derived from natural sources and nature derived compounds have historically served as promising leads especially for antibiotic drug discovery programs. A large number of antibacterial drugs (69%) approved in 1981–2006 are either natural compounds or have been developed from nature derived scaﬀolds. The current pipeline of antibiotics is relatively dry with very few com- pounds available to revolutionize antibacterial therapy, especially in the era of increased drug resistance, an outcome of indiscriminate use or misuse of existing antibiotics [29].

In addition to these three aminocoumarins, two other natural aminocoumarins have been dis- covered- rubradirin whose deoxysugar moiety lacks the 7-OH group of the aminocoumarin moiety and is not a gyrase inhibitor and the si- mocyclinones [36]. Aminocoumarins exhibit competitive DNA gyrase inhibitory activity while the clinically used ﬂuoroquinolones exhibit DNA poisoning activity. Aminocoumarins are the only class of DNA gyrase inhibitors used clinically in addition to ﬂuoroquinolones and show good activity against methicillin resistant S. aureus and ﬂuor- oquinolone-resistant strains. In spite of potent activity, their clinical success is limited due to eukaryotic toxicity, poor eﬃcacy against gram negative bacteria and low solubility resulting pharmaceutical problems [37].

Simocyclinones are novel natural hybrid antibiotics isolated from the fermentation broth of Streptomyces antibioticus. Fourteen diﬀerent angucyclinone antibiotics have been isolated till date and classiﬁed in four series, AeD. The simocyclinones of the A-series consist of an an- gucycline ring only, the compounds of series B are glycosylated, Biomedicine & Pharmacotherapy 103 (2018) 923–938 compounds of the C-series have a tetraene side-chain, and those of the D-series also have a coumarin ring system. Simocyclinone D8 (SD8) (4) inhibits DNA gyrase by a unique mechanism. It acts as a competitive inhibitor of DNA gyrase as against ﬂuoroquinolones that trap DNA in a covalent complex with enzyme and show distinct enzyme binding sites. SD8 (4) comprises of three subunits: a coumarin moiety, a tetraene linker and an angucyclinone aglycone that is consist of an olivose sugar bound to a highly substituted benz[a]anthracene system via a C-gly- coside bond [38]

Numerous simocyclinone variants are produced by S. antibiotics that are mostly intermediates of SD8 [39]. SD8 has only moderate anti- bacterial properties and is mostly active against gram-positive organ- isms such as Streptomyces viridochromogenes and ineﬀective against gram-negative organisms. It also exhibits cytotoxic activity in human cells by targeting human topoisomerase II enzyme [40]. It does not target the ATPase binding site of GyrB, which is located within the N- terminal domain but tends to bind at the N-terminal domain of GyrA at the region where DNA binds (Fig. 8.). Due to interaction of the ami- nocoumarin and angucylic polyketide with two separate binding pockets in the N-terminal domain of GyrA, it makes SD8 a ‘two headed antibiotic’ that prevents DNA binding [41]. The bicyclic ring system of the ﬂavones (isosteric replacement of the coumarin system of SD8) and the 2-phenyl ring of the ﬂavones occupied the hydrophobic cleft formed by Leu98, Gly170, and Tyr 266 that was adjacent to the coumarin binding site thereby creating additional binding interactions [42]. During 1992–1993, Roche reported a new lead structure i.e. cy- clothialidine (8), after screening 20,000 culture broths of DNA in E.coli. Cyclothialidine (Ro 09-1437), produced by Streptomyces ﬁlipinensis targeted DNA gyrase speciﬁcally by attaching to subunit B and blocking the ATPase activity. It exhibited poor penetration into the bacterial cytoplasmic cell membrane, hence, an extremely weak antimicrobial activity. However, it was active against E. coli DNA gyrase with 2-fold higher activity than both novobiocin (2) and coumermycin A1 (3) and about 29-fold higher than quinolones i.e. ciproﬂoxacin (30). On this basis 170 analogs of cyclothialidine were reported in the 1992. The MIC90 of Ro 46-9288 (9) was found to be much lesser than the corre- sponding MIC90 of novobiocin. Therefore, this analog was named as partially bactericidal. Roche and Bayer subsequently discovered acyclic cyclothialidine macrolactone scaﬀold Ro 61-6653 (10) that exhibited similar biochemical and microbiological potency as compared with cyclic analogs [43]. Glaxo discovered GR122222X (14), a cyclic peptide in 1996 and reported it to bind to subunit GyrB N-terminal domain at a site that overlaps the ATP-binding site. Cyclothialidines are competitive inhibitors of the ATPase gyrase activity similar to the classical amino- coumarins. Catechin- based polyphenols (from Green tea) Flavonoids traditionally consumed in human diet, are present in plants as natural ubiquitous polyphenolic substances. Green tea (Camellia sinensis) is an extensively consumed beverage that exhibits many promising beneﬁts on human health. Green tea extract is rich in catechin-based ﬂavonoids like (-)-epicatechin (EC (15), 4–6%), (-)-epicatechin-3- gallate (ECG (16), 10–20%), (-)-epigallocatechin (EGC (17), 10–20%) and (-)-epigallocatechin-3-gallate (EGCG (18) Biomedicine & Pharmacotherapy 103 (2018) 923–938 (40–60%) and displays versatile biological activity including anti- microbial activity. (Fig. 10.) Gradisar et.al evaluated EGCG, EGC, ECG, and EC for their ability to inhibit the ATPase activity and also de- termined their binding aﬃnity for gyrase B. The results indicated that EGCG had the highest activity, followed by ECG and EGC. They also reported these catechins block bacterial DNA gyrase by attaching to the gyrase B subunit at the ATP binding site. Molecular docking analysis indicated that the benzopyran ring of EGCG penetrates deeply into the active site while the galloyl moiety anchors it to the cleft through in- teractions with its hydroxyl groups, thereby justifying the higher ac- tivity of EGCG and ECG [47].

Chebulinic acid (CA) (26) is a compound obtained from Terminalia chebula that is active against various diseases and is one of the most promising candidates to treat tuberculosis (TB) and ﬂuoroquinolone- resistant mutant gyrase by targeting DNA gyrA. CA was found to change the shape of the enzyme that increased the distance from catalytic tyrosine residue at 129 position to DNA phosphate. Fig. 12 indicates the distance from the Tyr 129 of native DNA gyrase + DNA docked com- plex to DNA phosphate being 1.6 Å (in blue) and distances between Tyr129 of post- MD simulated DNA gyrA + CA complex (in brick red). In addition to this, CA structure tends to bind at DNA attaching site of DNA gyrA creating steric hindrance to the binding process. This led to non-functionality of DNA gyrase and subsequent failure in DNA re- plication in M. tuberculosis leading to its death. The results indicated CA as a promising candidate for drug design for treating wild type as well as a MDR and XDR TB [49]. 4.2. DNA gyrase inhibitors of synthetic origin Fluoroquinolones have been the most successful antibacterial agents targeting DNA gyrase. These compounds have been extensively ex- plored and researched to improve spectrum of activity, potency and bacterial resistance. Screening chemical libraries has yielded new scaﬀolds and chemical entities to combat the emerging resistance in the ﬁeld of microbial infections. The journey of quinolones and other se- lected scaﬀolds aptly represents the development of many versatile scaﬀolds as DNA gyrase inhibitors. Although DNA gyrase was discovered in E. coli in 1976, the classes of gyrase inhibitors were already known before this date. The Biomedicine & Pharmacotherapy 103 (2018) 923–938

quinolone, nalidixic acid, (27) was found accidentally as a side product in the synthesis of the antimalarial drug chloroquine [50]. Nalidixic acid, subsequently formed the basis of development of the ﬂuor- oquinolone class of compounds. The ﬂuoroquinolones work as poisons of DNA gyrase as they are able to stabilize the covalent gyrase-DNA complex, thereby leading to protein-stabilized DNA breaks and ulti- mately cell death [51]. The time line of the discovery of quinolones is depicted below (Fig. 13.). Nalidixic acid was discovered in 1962, introduced into the market in 1967 for treatment of urinary tract infections (UTIs) caused by enteric bacteria. This marked the genesis of more than ﬁfty years of quinolones development and use. However the quinolones were a neglected group of antimicrobials until the development of ﬂuoroquinolones in the 1970. The ﬂuoroquinolones showcased extended activity and improved pharmacokinetic proﬁles as compared to the already known analogues of quinolones. Proteinaceous inhibitors Two plasmid-encoded toxins CcdB and microcin B17 are targets of DNA gyrase which maintain plasmid integrity. These inhibitors stabilize covalent complexes of gyrase with DNA which are converted to break double strand leading to cell death. Microcin (Microcin B17) is a low molecular mass antibiotic about a 3.1 kDa. It is a glycine-rich peptide developed by enterobacteria car- rying the pMccB17 plasmid [57]. Modiﬁcation of peptide is done by converting serine and cysteine residues into oxazole, thiazole, and ox- azole-thiazole fused rings [58]. MccB17 is found to be active against enterobacteria and responsible for inhibiting DNA replication and in- duce DNA degradation and this leads to cell death [59]. It is linked to its ability to increase E. coli gyrase mediated double-strand cleavage of DNA. It is a weak inhibitor of DNA gyrase as compared with quinolones and works through a diﬀerent mode of action. The proteinaceous toxin does not completely inhibit the supercoiling and relaxation reactions of DNA gyrase but they help to slow down reaction by about three fold. MccB17 can weakly stabilize the cleavage complex in the absence of ATP, but in its presence of ATP cleavage complex is more eﬀectively stabilized [60].

CcdB is produced as a part of a two-component toxin–antitoxin system which is involved in the maintenance of the copy number of the F plasmid. It is about 11.7 kDa protein that is CcdB and found active in formed of dimer and easily inactivated by CcdA [61]. Its intracellular target is DNA gyrase. CcdB inhibits bacteria by similar mechanism as of quinolones as it involves stabilization of the cleavage complex of DNA with gyrase. The mutation of Arg462 to Cys in GyrA leads to form gyrase resistance to CcdB [62]. According to biochemical evidence major diﬀerences exist in the mechanism of quinolones and CcdB i.e. CcdB induced cleavage of DNA requires nucleotides (ATP for linear or relaxed DNA and a non-hydrolysable nucleotide for negatively super- coiled DNA) and DNA templates of at least 160 bp while quinolone induced cleavage does not require ATP and DNA substrates of 20 bp can be cleaved [63]. ParE/ParD is another example of a toxin antitoxin system. It is ob- tained by the RK2 plasmid of E-coli and has been observed to inhibit DNA synthesis and stabilize cleavage complex of gyrase with DNA. Its mode of gyrase inhibition is quite distinct in that it requires ATP and inhibits supercoiling and not relaxation [64]. 4.2.3. Pentapeptide repeat proteins

These are a large (> 500) family of pentapeptides comprising of tandemly repeated 5-amino acid motif [72] for e.g. Qnr, obtained from K. pneumoniae. It binds to the enzyme before binding of DNA gyrase to quinolones. So, apparently it protects resistance of ﬂuroquinolones [73,74]. Conﬁrmation about the mode of action was carried out by using Qnr homologue i.e. MfpA obtained from M. tuberculosis that in- dicated protein adopts structure like DNA with right handed quad- rilateral β- sheet comprised of the pentapeptide repeats. According to modeling study this motif mimics DNA by binds to DNA gyrase at an A subunit. But, structure of Qnr bound to Gyr A has not reported yet. One more Qnr analogue is reported which structure similar to MfpA which is obtained from E. faecalis [75]. The indispensable nature of topoisomerases and the diﬀerences between the prokaryote and eukaryote enzymes has made them ideal targets for chemotherapeutic agents. The advent of high-resolution structural information for parts of the topoisomerase molecules has made structure-based drug design convenient and eﬀective. Some of these compounds have been reported to function as anticancer agents harnessing the same therapeutic target i.e. DNA gyrase. This review deliberates on the structural modiﬁcations in templates like cyclothia- lidines and haloemodin analogues obtained from natural sources that contribute to better activity versus the current drugs used to treat bacterial infections.
